MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: cartridges/games/[^/]+/[^/]+Renderer\.tsx
MATCH_CONTENT: (visibilityState|document\.hidden|cancelAnimationFrame|requestAnimationFrame\(\s*(null|undefined)|chrome-profile|--isolated)
ADVISORY: |
  When play-testing a canvas renderer via a browser MCP, verify the
  tab is foregrounded BEFORE debugging the renderer code.

  Chrome throttles `requestAnimationFrame` to ~0 calls/sec in hidden
  tabs (`document.visibilityState === 'hidden'`). The useEffect mounts,
  the first RAF is scheduled, but no frame ever fires, so nothing is
  drawn. The canvas stays fully transparent. Easy to mis-diagnose as
  broken renderer logic.

  Diagnostic one-liner (via mcp__claude-in-chrome__javascript_tool):
    ({ vis: document.visibilityState, focus: document.hasFocus() })

  Only `visibilityState === 'visible'` matters — `hasFocus()` false is
  fine for RAF.

  Related trap: the separate `chrome-devtools-mcp` tools use their own
  Chrome profile at `~/.cache/chrome-devtools-mcp/chrome-profile` which
  conflicts with the user's running Chrome. Use `mcp__claude-in-chrome__*`
  to drive the user's own browser session. Error signature for the
  profile conflict: "The browser is already running for /Users/.../
  chrome-profile. Use --isolated to run multiple browser instances."
